Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Thu, 9 Sep 1993 07:09:28 GMT

In article <strobl.747404802@gmd.de> strobl@gmd.de (Wolfgang Strobl) writes:
>In <CCwuEC.5rL@frobozz.sccsi.com> kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown) writes:
>
>>In article <930904.130601.6K0.rusnews.w165w@mulvey.com> rich@mulvey.com (Rich Mulvey) writes:
[...]
>>>   Sure - it's badly designed *IN RETROSPECT*.
>
>>No, it was badly designed even by the standards of the time.  Remember that
>>the 68000 was out at this point, and it was far and away superior to the
>>CPU that IBM decided to use.
>
>IBM choosed the 8088 mainly because it is almost upward compatible with
>the 8080 processor on the assembler level. Most of the popular software
>during the first years of the IBM PC was the result of running the
>assembly code of a CP/M program through a very simple translator which
>did a simple one-to-one opcode and register mapping. WordStar was the
>result of such a quick port. So was dBase II. PCDOS 1 made this possible
>by almost completely emulating the CP/M interface, including such 
>techniques as putting a jump to the terminating code into location
>0 and a JSR into the OS into location 5 in the Program Segment Prefix
>in order to support CP/Ms calling conventions.

*Groan*.  I suppose it might be something of a win to do that sort of thing,
but it sure is a shortsighted "solution" to the problem.

Were WordStar and dBase II originally written in assembly or something?  If
not, then why not simply implement the appropriate languages first?

>IMHO, this was much more important for the success of the IBM PC
>than anything else.

That could be.  My personal opinion is that the success of the IBM PC was
primarily a result of the IBM name (which, to a business at the time,
meant quite a bit).  From that frame of reference, CP/M compatibility
means diddly.  Business software houses were scrambling all over themselves
porting their products to the IBM PC.  Want an example?  Look at PeachTree
accounting, which was running primarily (I believe) on the Apple II at the
time.  If I recall correctly, it came out for the PC only a couple of months
after the PC hit the market.  I was working for a computer store at the
time and remember this kind of thing happening.  It didn't suprise me at
all...

>>The cheap clone market didn't come until well after the PC had established
>>itself.  It came *because* of the popularity of the PC.
>
>>Recall that even the Apple II had clones, namely the Franklin.
>
>True, but Apple put a lot of effort into preventing other people
>from cloning their computers. IBM didn't do that - which is the
>second reason why the architecture was such a success. The PS/2
>failed, because people (rightfully) suspected that IBM intended
>to lock them into their hardware line, just like Apple does
>it with their Macintosh line.

Now *this* I agree with 100%.  My original statement still stands, though:
manufacturers of clones wouldn't have bothered if the PC weren't successful
on its own.  It would be much more of a risk to clone a machine that hadn't
proven itself to be popular.

>>>   See above.  Hindsight is 20/20.
>
>>So?  The lessons that were presumably taught by the previous generation of
>>computers had already been learned by many.  But not by IBM and not by
>>Microsoft.  I knew back before the PC came out that memory limitations
>>should be a result of a limited pocketbook, not a limited design.  I had
>>seen the growth in the size of software and extrapolated appropriately.
>>Many others had as well.  So why the 640k absolute limit, when the 68000
>>had a 16 meg limit?
>
>A design is always limited. In what way is 16M better than 1M? 

It's an order of magnitude larger, which means you have that much more
room for growth, which means it'll be that much longer before you have to
redesign.

In particular, it's only *now*, 12 years after the PC came out, that we're
starting to routinely use that much memory.  But it was only a couple of
years after the PC came out that people started hitting the 640k barrier.

>Supporting
>only a flat, linear address space is a limited design, when compared
>with segmented memory, IMHO.

This seems to be basically a religious thing.  :-)  Suffice it to say that
each has its ups and downs.

I actually agree that a segmented architecture can be a win, *if* the
segments are as large as your physical address space.  The PC's weren't,
and that's why programmers came to hate the architecture.  It made doing
large arrays *really* painful.

>What was the first thing Apple did when they implemented the memory management
>for the Mac? Right: they implemented memory segmenting on the 68000,
>quite similar to the 286s 64K segmenting, without bounds checking and, 
>of course, they had to do in software what the 80286 (and in a much
>more limited way the 8088) did completely in hardware. At the same time,
>they invented the 32K segment and the 8MByte-limit. :-)

Perhaps, but they didn't *have* to do it that way.  The Amiga is based on
the 68000 and does no such thing (has a blazingly fast windowing system
and operating system, too).

In a protected multitasking environment, segments are probably a win, 
again *if* the segments can be as large as the external addressing space 
(on the 386/486, they can be).  What this means is that *within a 
process* you want a flat addressing space.  Within a process, segments 
don't buy you anything (that I've seen.  I'm sure there are *some* uses, 
but I haven't seen them), particularly when you have lots of 
general-purpose registers and base+offset addressing like the 68000 has, 
and if your segments are small (like they are on the 808x) you lose 
bigtime.  





