Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: rdippold@qualcomm.com (Ron "Asbestos" Dippold)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Fri, 10 Sep 1993 12:11:33 GMT

kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown) writes:
>That could be.  My personal opinion is that the success of the IBM PC was
>primarily a result of the IBM name (which, to a business at the time,

As one who was heavily involved into pcs of all sort, including the
business end, even back then, I've got to quote the magic mantra:
Lotus 1-2-3.

I've still got magazines from back then with 123 ads all over the
place, editorials and articles gushing about how great it was, etc.
The Big Application of the time was spreadsheets - more so than any
category I can think of today, except maybe graphical operating
systems.  People who had been going wild over Apple ][s and VisiCalc
suddenly had something better.  Plus the IBM name on the PCs.  This
marked the PC as "the" business machine in the eyes of the software
companies and they started cranking them out.  And you started getting
hard drives for all your precious Lotus data - 5 meggers, or if you
had tons of money, ten megs (gasp)!

DOS at the time was horrible, much worse than what was available at
the time (hell, Apple DOS 3.3 blew it away).  The compilers reeked
(this was before Borland started giving them major competition and
forced them to consider the virtues of optimization).  But WordStar
was ported fairly quickly, so the PC had the premiere word processor
of its day.

-- 
You have nothing to fear but fear itself... oh, yeah, and that exam next week.

